/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Yuki Yoi","active":true,"timeZone":"Asia/Tokyo"},"created":"2012-10-21T09:17:10.895+0000","updated":"2012-10-21T09:17:10.895+0000"},{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/12601520/comment/13481011","id":"13481011","author":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=ashutoshc","name":"ashutoshc","key":"ashutoshc","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Ashutosh Chauhan","active":true,"timeZone":"America/Los_Angeles"},"body":"Couple of comments:\n* In finally block, instead of {{reader.close();}} better is to do {{org.apache.hadoop.io.IOUtils.closeStream(reader);}} since reader could be either null or can throw IOException in close(). IOUtils handles both of those cases.\n* Same problem exists even in unit test code of this class, where reader.close() is never invoked, resulting in socket leak. In both tests testAccuracy1() and testAccuracy2() can you add {{reader.close()}} I don't think we need to do full try-catch-block in testcases, since there as soon as exception occurs we want to start unwinding the stack.","updateAuthor":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=ashutoshc","name":"ashutoshc","key":"ashutoshc","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Ashutosh Chauhan","active":true,"timeZone":"America/Los_Angeles"},"